/*Character style guide time!! This is my explanation for why I wrote characters with certain speech mannerisms & patterns, and also is meant to
assist anybody who's trying to retranslate parts of this if they want something closer to the original Japanese. Japanese has a much wider range
of distinction between different styles and "archetypes" of speech, whereas in English it's alot more about:
- intonation (difficult to put into text but not IMPOSSIBLE, I'm definitely an italic text fan haha)
- expression (can't be put into text)
- voice (again, difficult to put into text)
- word choice
- word order/wording in general
those last two are absolutely essential to giving each character a distinct sound, with intonation & voice being like the little garnish on top
that brings it all together. Japanese meanwhile has tons of ways to end a sentence and tons of sentence-ending particles, which make differences
in speech patterns in Japanese stand out. There's also a bit of a wild card too that's interesting to try to translate around, but I'll be sure to
introduce that. Let's talk about all the characters now:

==CHIEF==
Ah yes, the "wise old man" archetype. I was more limited than I wanted to be, but him talking in an older style helped with wording.

In Japanese, he uses these distinct speech patterns:
- Sentence-ender じゃ as opposed to だ is usually used amongst older people as well as to distinguish old people in media like games/manga/etc.
However, it still does see some use in some regions of Japan even among younger people.
- ぞい is the archaic form of sentence-ending particle ぜ, and is a combination of ぞ (heavy masculine emphasis) and い (friendly/familiar yet
slightly forceful). ぜ often indicates a large amount of confidence, and as the chief is a former master hunter, I did try to keep this confidence.
- Says negative tense verbs with ん instead of ない -- in the Chief's case, that's because it stems from ぬ, which is an archaic auxiliary verb that
indicates negative tense. You'll see another case of ん being used later.
- Commands are verb+のじゃ -- technically, this is moreso just emphasizing that somebody else (like the hunter) will do something he says, but the
general use in English is that of a request/command.

In English, I used these methods of translating his speech patterns:
- Use archaic wording when possible. For example, in the line "You've a well-done steak", this wasn't only done because of the character limit but
also because that sort of wording is common in more archaic language. Now, the only thing with this is that it's critical to keep it from being
overbearing! Don't make him sound TOO old, or it just turns out ridiculous (i.e. no "thou", "thy", etc).
- Keep him confident! This guy was the Hero of Kokoto in his prime, when it comes to teaching you he sure knows what he's doing!
- Don't make him sound too casual either, no "young'un" or "lad", especially with those two terms it implies he's American or Scottish, and it's best
not to imply characters are from a certain real-life region.

==Smith==
A quite literally hardheaded blacksmith, he gives off the vibes of somebody experienced in their trade, probably around his 40-50s if I had to guess.
He was fun to do!

In Japanese, he uses these distinct speech patterns:
- Sentence-ending particle い as explained above has a sort of familiar-and-friendly slight force, and is often used from older people to younger people.
This is used mostly in questions.
- Sentence-ending particle ぜ gives a familiar-yet-forceful meaning. This is often seen as masculine (tho not used by only men) and even moreso gives off
vibes of confidence.
- Sentence-ending particle な adds emphasis to a statement and lightly seeks agreement, while being moderately forceful.
- His form of asking 

In English, I used these methods of translating his speech patterns:
- Using "ya" in place of "you" in most (but not ALL) cases gives off that similar vibe of familiar-and-friendly but with light force.
- Certain phrasing was also used to give off a similar vibe, particularly I did this when the phrasing in Japanese was something common in Japanese but not
in English.
- I made sure to stray away from phrasing such as "ain't" that, while common amongst alot of people with that speech vibe, isn't really reflected in the
original Japanese.

==Armory==
Likely younger than the smith, but not inexperienced. He seems younger, and maybe almost a bit nerdy.

In Japanese, he uses these distinct speech patterns:
- He talks in formal speech, compared to everybody else.
- Though he speaks formally, he doesn't speak without emotion. Some of his lines about being a "ticket enthusiast" lead to him seeming almost a bit nerdy.

In English, I used these methods of translating his speech patterns:
- Keeping flavor in his speech subtle, but not nonexistent. He values the customer and their time, but still has a personality!